post_text:
With the elementary construction project coming to a close this week and our commitment to the health and safety of our school and community, we have made the decision to push back the start date for Frazee-Vergas Schools to Monday, September 14th.
Elementary students will be given an opportunity next week to meet their teachers and see their classroom and building updates. High School students will also be given opportunities to meet with counselors to make schedule changes and pick up chromebooks. Look for communication from the school in the coming days on dates and times.

Students in grades 7-12 have the opportunity to pick up their Chromebook prior to school starting next week. Chromebook pickup will be tomorrow, Thursday, September 10th at Door #2 of the high school from 2:00-6:00 p.m. Please bring the signed agreement form (sent out in your back to school mailing)with you when you come. There will also be some available to fill out if you didn't receive one.
If you have a Chromebook or textbooks from distance learning last spring, please bring those as well.
Please remember to wear a mask and maintain social distancing guidelines when you come to pick up.

Hornet Families, the U.S Department of Agriculture & Food and Nutrition Services has provided waivers to extend the Summer Food Service Program and Seamless Summer Option operations into the school year until funds are exhausted. Students enrolled in the Frazee-Vergas School District will receive free breakfast and lunch until funds run out.
Please remember to complete the free & reduced lunch application (found at the link below) as the end date of this offering is unknown.
Grab and Go lunches, for enrolled Frazee-Vergas students in either distance learning or a hybrid learning day, will be available from 1:30-2:00 on days school is in session; please use door #20 for pickup. Please call the district office at 218-334-3181 ext. 5601 if you have any questions.

post_text: Last evening, the school board passed a resolution regarding the learning models for the 2020-2021 school year. On September 8, the Frazee-Vergas Elementary School will start the year in-person and the Frazee High School will start the year in the hybrid model. More details regarding the models will be sent out by email to district families by the building principals later this week. The annual back to school mailing sent out will have additional information as well.

post_text:
School Supply Drive Distribution benefiting Lakes Area Students in Need

Wednesday, Aug 26, 2020
4:00 PM - 6:00 PM

post_text: The upside to today's meeting is we still will have activities at FHS. Cross Country is still on schedule to compete this fall in an abbreviated season. Football and Volleyball will be moved to a spring season, with possibly an option to practice this fall. (I have much to learn this week on all this) Many questions and uncertain thoughts regarding these decisions today, but we need to remember they were made with the best intent to help our communities and students. These are tough decisions the MSHSL was asked to make and we need to do our best to make the most of it. Remember we still have activities this fall at FHS and still have much to look forward to! More information to come this week and next week on how we move forward.

post_text:
Virtual Art Class

Learn to draw some of your favorite comic characters and techniques to draw your own! This is a great opportunity to learn new drawing skills and push yourself to become a better comic artist. This class is taught entirely through Zoom, so you can draw along at home. Directions to login and handouts will be emailed to you prior to the week's classes, just print them to follow along. Aryn Lill, The Blue Fox, is a long time Community Education instructor. Supplies YOU must provide include: drawing paper, pencil, eraser, sharpie, colored pencils and a computer with internet access and Zoom downloaded. The fee is $20 per day (additional family members $15).

To Register: https://frazee.revtrak.net/tek9.asp?pg=ws_redirect&Extra_params=newurl~eventDetail.html%3Fid%3D1138929

post_text:
As we enter the last few days of the school year I want to thank you all for a great school year. We miss seeing everyone. You all have done a great job with distance learning. We look forward to picking up where we left off the fall. I hope everyone has a great summer! We would like to say one last hello and a goodbye until we see you again.

On Wednesday the 20th from 5:30-6:30 we will have a teacher parade for Elementary students, families and staff. Staff will line up in the back parking lot of the high school, 6 feet apart making a curved line from the kitchen overhead door, along the building to the white garage. Families will come up 2nd street NW, pull into the first parking lot entrance drive through the parking lot and out the second entrance of the parking lot by the white garage and proceed down 2nd street NW.

Travis Nagel

post_text: On Monday, May 4th, we received confirmation from the Minnesota Department of Education stating they can not allow a graduation ceremony, even with proper social distancing measures in place, prior to the lifting of our state's current stay-at home order. As a result, the decision has been made to postpone indefinitely our Class of 2020 Commencement Ceremony originally scheduled for May 17, 2020. Senior Awards Night, previously scheduled for May 14, 2020, is also postponed indefinitely. As soon as we receive guidance from the Minnesota Department of Education and Minnesota Department of Health, we will identify new dates for these events. We have been working hard to plan events that recognize and celebrate this year‚Äôs graduating class without putting anyone‚Äôs health or safety at risk, and we look forward to putting these plans into action just as soon as we are allowed! The last day of school for seniors will remain Thursday, May 14th.

Attention seniors and parents of seniors: Caps and gowns can be picked up on Friday from 1-3 pm at Door 17.

If you have a black cap and gown that fits, you may use that in lieu of a new one. If you have a black cap/gown to trade in, you may do that at the pick-up.

Caps and gowns must be paid for before being picked up, or you must bring one to trade in. Refunds for trade-ins will be taken care of at a later date.

Please remember to practice social distancing and remain in your vehicle.

post_text: As you may have heard, with the safety and well being of our students at the forefront, Governor Walz has extended distance learning through the rest of the school year. Student instruction will not be held on May 1 and 4, per Governor Walz, as these days will be utilized as professional development days to prepare for the remainder of the school year in a distance learning environment. School-age child care for children of essential workers and meal delivery will still operate on these days. If you have any questions, please contact us at 218-334-3181.

post_text: Starting Monday, April 20, Childcare for school-age children of essential workers will change locations from the elementary to the high school commons. Hours will remain 7:30 a.m to 3:30 p.m. When dropping off your son/daughter, please pull up to door #17 of the High School and call 218-334-3181 ext. 5555. A childcare worker will meet your child at the door and bring them to the commons area. When you arrive to pick them up, call the same number and a childcare worker will bring your son/daughter out door #17. If you have any questions, please call 218-334-3181 ext. 5601

post_text:
Community Education Classes POSTPONED
March 17-March 30, 2020

Good Day Community Education Instructors and Students! Today, Governor Tim Walz announced that all Minnesota public schools will be closing due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The Frazee-Vergas Public Schools are closed Tuesday, March 17 through March 27, 2020 at this time. As always, our first priority is the safety and well-being of our patrons. We will continue to keep you informed as we navigate the COVID-19 situation and when classes resume and are rescheduled. Thank you kindly for your time and understanding.

March 17-March 30, 2020

Good Day Community Education Instructors and Students! Today, Governor Tim Walz announced that all Minnesota public schools will be closing due to the COVID-19 pandemic. The Frazee-Vergas Public Schools are closed Tuesday, March 17 through March 27, 2020 at this time. As always, our first priority is the safety and well-being of our patrons. We will continue to keep you informed as we navigate the COVID-19 situation and when classes resume and are rescheduled. Thank you kindly for your time and understanding.

Foundations Of French Pastry

Instructor: Mark Bridge
Many of today‚Äôs most basic of pastry preparations were either born or refined in the kitchens of France. However, despite the centuries-old techniques, home cooks can find them intimidating. Join Mark, who is certified in the culinary world, in this hands-on class. You will gain knowledge and practice skills to make successful pastries. This class will cover laminated dough technique (croissants), pate choux, creme patissiere, pate - sucree, sablee, and foncer. These are essential foundation items and techniques for many pastry items. The skills and tips you learn in this class will transfer over to some of the recipes and techniques in the other classes or stand on their own. Your fee includes all supplies.

Frazee‚Äôs United Way‚Äôs Day Of Caring

United Way‚Äôs Day of Caring is one day each year where volunteers set aside a few hours to give back to the community through a morning of helping. Teams of volunteers from the Frazee High School gather to complete much needed tasks such as raking, window washing, litter pick-up, spring cleaning, landscaping, gardening, and general repairs. It‚Äôs a single day of service with a big community impact. Last year we had 400 plus students and 40 staff who took to the streets, lawns, schools, parks, and senior centers to give back to over 60 families in our area. Participants must reside in the Frazee-Vergas district. If you are interested in being a part of this year‚Äôs Day of Caring, please call and pre-register.

Risky Apps To Watch Out For

Instructor: Gretchen Norby
Not every app is meant for kids--even if minors are technically allowed to use them. The discussion will include apps that are popular among kids but are potentially dangerous and problematic. What is Voxer? If you're scratching your head, it's time to learn more about trendy new social media apps kids are using. Friending your child on Facebook is now just the tip of the iceberg when it comes to online safety. Join us as we discuss some of the sites and apps tweens and teens are flocking to these days, and get useful tips for protecting your child from cyberbullying and other online safety hazards.
